01:07:31.248 --> 01:07:35.415
So I did a project on speech
in people, well I guess,

01:07:37.215 --> 01:07:41.298
the corpus of Tinder
biographies of millennials.

01:07:42.257 --> 01:07:43.130
- Corpus of what?

01:07:43.130 --> 01:07:45.518
- Tinder biographies, like the dating app.

01:07:45.518 --> 01:07:47.422
And one of the biggest challenges I had

01:07:47.422 --> 01:07:49.929
was that there's so
much visual information

01:07:49.929 --> 01:07:52.925
in people's photographs and in emoji use.

01:07:52.925 --> 01:07:54.411
And so I guess I was wondering,

01:07:54.411 --> 01:07:56.129
you mentioned the use of

01:07:56.129 --> 01:08:00.216
sort of, emojis, emoticon, bitmoji, memes,

01:08:00.216 --> 01:08:03.049
and how do you compensate for that

01:08:04.372 --> 01:08:05.719
or accommodate for that

01:08:05.719 --> 01:08:08.784
when so much of corpus
linguistics analysis

01:08:08.784 --> 01:08:11.547
is so like, quantitative,

01:08:11.547 --> 01:08:12.894
which is part of why I like it.

01:08:12.894 --> 01:08:15.912
Because it's quite easy
to sift through things,

01:08:15.912 --> 01:08:18.118
but when images come into play,

01:08:18.118 --> 01:08:21.091
it really kind of messes with my data.

01:08:21.091 --> 01:08:22.948
And so, I guess a question would be,

01:08:22.948 --> 01:08:25.526
how do you accommodate for
that in doing your work?

01:08:25.526 --> 01:08:28.289
- Yeah, corpus linguistics is a very very

01:08:28.289 --> 01:08:30.053
burgeoning field right now.

01:08:30.053 --> 01:08:32.735
And it's an amazing capability.

01:08:32.735 --> 01:08:35.313
You can get millions of words, data,

01:08:35.313 --> 01:08:37.147
and find answers that you know.

01:08:37.147 --> 01:08:39.260
I give you examples from a couple people,

01:08:39.260 --> 01:08:40.862
you gotta take my word for it

01:08:40.862 --> 01:08:42.511
that this is more widespread.

01:08:42.511 --> 01:08:43.858
And I trust you.

01:08:43.858 --> 01:08:45.158
Does it ring true?

01:08:45.158 --> 01:08:47.201
If it rings true, maybe
there's something to it.

01:08:47.201 --> 01:08:48.920
If you say, I've never
seen anything like that,

01:08:48.920 --> 01:08:51.149
maybe I got a weird example.

01:08:51.149 --> 01:08:53.285
So corpus linguistics is great that way.

01:08:53.285 --> 01:08:56.118
But I don't think it is capable of

01:08:57.325 --> 01:08:59.742
identifying these subtleties.

01:09:00.646 --> 01:09:02.178
So I think we need both.

01:09:02.178 --> 01:09:03.687
There are certain kinds of questions

01:09:03.687 --> 01:09:06.358
that can be addressed that
way and others that can't.

01:09:06.358 --> 01:09:08.633
I guess my concern is,

01:09:08.633 --> 01:09:11.907
there's a tendency to do
the things you can do.

01:09:11.907 --> 01:09:14.322
And that's my one concern, that

01:09:14.322 --> 01:09:17.759
as corpus linguistics
and computational methods

01:09:17.759 --> 01:09:19.547
become more and more widespread,

01:09:19.547 --> 01:09:21.079
we won't be asking the questions

01:09:21.079 --> 01:09:24.493
that have to be answered this way.

01:09:24.493 --> 01:09:27.952
Could call it a case study
method or microanalysis.

01:09:27.952 --> 01:09:30.089
But I think we need both.

01:09:30.089 --> 01:09:31.505
- And then I guess, perhaps this,

01:09:31.505 --> 01:09:33.804
you've just answered this potentially,

01:09:33.804 --> 01:09:35.568
but I guess, do you think that

01:09:35.568 --> 01:09:37.519
the changes you've seen like the one

01:09:37.519 --> 01:09:39.725
you just described with lol initially

01:09:39.725 --> 01:09:41.234
meaning I'm actually laughing

01:09:41.234 --> 01:09:42.952
to meaning just sort of, I'm amused,

01:09:42.952 --> 01:09:45.619
do you think there's any sort of

01:09:48.360 --> 01:09:51.127
language change analyses
that can be applied

01:09:51.127 --> 01:09:54.656
